Description: An HTTP server in C++ 98

You must write an HTTP server in C++ 98.
Your executable should be executed as follows:
./webserv [configuration file]

Even though poll() is mentioned in the subject and evaluation sheet,
you can use any equivalent function such as select(), kqueue(), or epoll().

Requirements
• Your program must use a configuration file, provided as an argument on the command line, or available in a default path.
• You cannot execve another web server.
• Your server must remain non-blocking at all times and properly handle client disconnections when necessary.
• It must be non-blocking and use only 1 poll() (or equivalent) for all the I/O operations between the clients and the server (listen included).
• poll() (or equivalent) must monitor both reading and writing simultaneously.
• You must never do a read or a write operation without going through poll() (or equivalent).
• Checking the value of errno to adjust the server behaviour is strictly forbidden after performing a read or write operation.
• You are not required to use poll() (or equivalent) before read() to retrieve your configuration file.

Because you have to use non-blocking file descriptors, it is possible to use read/recv or write/send functions with no poll() (or equivalent), and your server wouldn’t be blocking.
But it would consume more system resources.
Thus, if you attempt to read/recv or write/send on any file descriptor without using poll() (or equivalent), your grade will be 0.

• When using poll() or any equivalent call, you can use every associated macro or helper function (e.g., FD_SET for select()).
• A request to your server should never hang indefinitely.
• Your server must be compatible with standard web browsers of your choice.
• NGINX may be used to compare headers and answer behaviours (pay attention to differences between HTTP versions).
• Your HTTP response status codes must be accurate.
• Your server must have default error pages if none are provided.
• You can’t use fork for anything other than CGI (like PHP, or Python, and so forth).
• You must be able to serve a fully static website.
• Clients must be able to upload files.

• You need at least the GET, POST, and DELETE methods.
• Stress test your server to ensure it remains available at all times.
• Your server must be able to listen to multiple ports to deliver different content (see Configuration file).







The Reactor Pattern

At its core, the Reactor Pattern allows a single-threaded application to handle multiple concurrent I/O events (like client connections, reads, writes) without blocking.
Rather than having a thread per connection (which doesn't scale well), the Reactor pattern:
- Listens for I/O events
- Demultiplexes them (figures out what event happened and on which socket)
- Dispatches them to the correct handler (like onRead, onWrite, etc.)

example of a simle reactor pattern:
class Reactor 
{
	public:
		Reactor();
		~Reactor();
		// copy and assignment operator
		void run();
		void add_fd(int epoll_fd, int fd, uint32_t events);

	private:
		int server_fd;
		void handle_accept();
		void handle_read(int fd);
		void handle_write(int fd);
};


Reactor::void run() 
{
	int epoll_fd = epoll_create1(0);
	if (epoll_fd == -1) 
	{
		perror("epoll_create1");
		return;
	}

	// Add server socket to epoll
	add_fd(epoll_fd, server_fd, EPOLLIN);

	struct epoll_event events[10];
	while (true) 
	{
		int n = epoll_wait(epoll_fd, events, 10, -1);
		for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) 
		{
			int fd = events[i].data.fd;

			if (fd == server_fd) 
			{
				handle_accept(); // Accept new client
			} 
			else if (events[i].events & EPOLLIN) 
			{
				handle_read(fd);
			} 
			else if (events[i].events & EPOLLOUT) 
			{
				handle_write(fd);
			}
		}
	}
}

Reactor::void add_fd(int epoll_fd, int fd, uint32_t events) 
{
	struct epoll_event ev;
	ev.events = events;
	ev.data.fd = fd;
	if (epoll_ctl(epoll_fd, EPOLL_CTL_ADD, fd, &ev) == -1) 
	{
		perror("epoll_ctl: add_fd");
	}
}

Reactor::void handle_accept() 
{
	int client_fd = accept(server_fd, NULL, NULL);
	// Set non-blocking
	fcntl(client_fd, F_SETFL, O_NONBLOCK);
	add_fd(epoll_fd, client_fd, EPOLLIN);
}

Reactor::void handle_read(int fd) 
{
	char buffer[1024];
	int n = read(fd, buffer, sizeof(buffer));
	if (n <= 0) 
	{
		close(fd);
	} 
	else 
	{
		std::cout << "Received: " << std::string(buffer, n) << std::endl;
		// You could set EPOLLOUT here to write back
	}
}

Reactor::void handle_write(int fd) 
{
	// write response to fd
}



What to Research First
Here's a breakdown of the core topics you must research before you start coding:

1. HTTP Protocol (RFC 2616 / 7230)
- Learn how HTTP/1.1 works:
    - Request line (GET /index.html HTTP/1.1)
    - Headers (Host, Content-Length, Content-Type)
    - Body (for POST requests)
    - Status codes (200 OK, 404 Not Found, etc.)
    - Keep-alive vs connection: close
- Research how browsers send requests
- Understand chunked transfer encoding.

Resources:

- MDN HTTP Overview 	-> 		https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Guides/Overview
- RFC 7230 (HTTP/1.1 semantics)


2. Reactor Pattern & Non-blocking I/O
You're forced to use poll(), select(), epoll, or kqueue. Learn:
- The Reactor Pattern
- How to:
    - Make a socket non-blocking with fcntl
    - Use poll() or epoll to multiplex I/O
    - Accept new clients and serve them without threads
-Your server must be single-threaded and non-blocking. All reads/writes must go through poll() (or equivalent).

Resources:

    Beej’s Guide to Network Programming			-> 		https://beej.us/guide/bgnet/
	Linux epoll tutorial						-> 		https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man7/epoll.7.html


3. Configuration File Parsing
You must read a configuration file defining:
- Ports to listen on
- Server roots
- Default error pages
- Allowed HTTP methods per location
- CGI config, etc.

Think like NGINX config:
server
{
    listen 8080;
    root /var/www/html;

    location /upload 
	{
        methods POST;
    }

    error_page 404 /errors/404.html;
}

You’ll need to:
- Write a custom parser (can't use modern C++ STL parsing tools).
- Validate and structure this config into objects.

4. File System + HTTP Response Building
Understand how to:
    - Open and serve files (with open, read, stat, access)
    - Serve correct content types (Content-Type)
    - Build proper HTTP responses: headers + body

Bonus:
    - Understand MIME types
    - Handle range headers for file seeking (optional)

5. Error Handling
    - Return proper status codes (403, 404, 500, etc.)
    - Serve default error pages
    - Handle edge cases: too large requests, malformed requests, timeouts

6. CGI Handling
    - For POST requests to /cgi-bin/script.py, fork+exec the script
    - Communicate with the child process via pipe()
    - Read output from script and include it in HTTP response


Where to Start

Here’s a step-by-step plan:

Step 1: Basic TCP Server
- Create a simple TCP server
- Use poll() to accept and echo data from clients
- Set sockets to non-blocking
- Try poll() on a single socket, then multiple clients

Step 2: HTTP Request Parser
- Parse raw HTTP request into:
	- Method
	- Path
	- Headers
	- Body
- Handle GET and return a basic HTML page

Step 3: Response Generator
- Build correct HTTP responses:
	- Content-Type, Content-Length
	- Status line
- Start with static responses

Step 4: Serve Static Files
- Based on the request path, read file from disk and send it
- Handle 404 if file doesn’t exist

Step 5: Add Configuration Parsing
- Write a minimal parser for a sample config file
- Load server port, root directory, etc.
- Support multiple virtual hosts

Step 6: Implement POST / File Upload
- Handle POST requests with file data
- Save uploaded file to disk

Step 7: Implement DELETE
- If DELETE is allowed in config, remove the requested file

Step 8: Implement CGI
- Fork a child process
- Execute the CGI script
- Capture stdout and send it back as HTTP response

Step 9: Stress Test + Edge Cases
- Keep-alive vs close
- Slowloris attacks
- Browser compatibility
- Memory leaks (check with Valgrind)
